SIMPLE: ignite
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ignite
<hw>Ig*nite"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧g*n⟦imac⟧t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ignited</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Igniting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>ignitus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>ignire</ets> to ignite, fr.
<ets>ignis</ets> fire. See <er>Igneous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
kindle or set on fire; <as>as, to <ex>ignite</ex> paper or
wood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To subject to the action of
intense heat; to heat strongly; -- often said of incombustible or
infusible substances; <as>as, to <ex>ignite</ex> iron or
platinum</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ignite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ignite
<hw>Ig*nite"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take fire; to begin to
burn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>ignited</ent>⟦br⟧
